  "prompt": "How do I find the average acceleration?",
  "response": "You can find the average acceleration using the following formula:\n\n**Average Acceleration (a<sub>avg</sub>) = (Change in Velocity (\u0394v)) / (Change in Time (\u0394t))**\n\nHere's a breakdown of each part and how to use the formula:\n\n1.  **Change in Velocity (\u0394v):**\n\n    *   This represents the difference between the final velocity and the initial velocity.\n    *   **\u0394v = v<sub>f</sub> - v<sub>i</sub>**\n        *   v<sub>f</sub> = Final velocity\n        *   v<sub>i</sub> = Initial velocity\n\n2.  **Change in Time (\u0394t):**\n\n    *   This represents the difference between the final time and the initial time.\n    *   **\u0394t = t<sub>f</sub> - t<sub>i</sub>**\n        *   t<sub>f</sub> = Final time\n        *   t<sub>i</sub> = Initial time\n\n**Putting it all together:**\n\n**a<sub>avg</sub> = (v<sub>f</sub> - v<sub>i</sub>) / (t<sub>f</sub> - t<sub>i</sub>)**\n\n**Steps to Calculate Average Acceleration:**\n\n1.  **Identify the Initial Velocity (v<sub>i</sub>) and Final Velocity (v<sub>f</sub>):**  Pay attention to the direction of the motion. Velocity is a vector, so direction matters (e.g., positive for moving right, negative for moving left).\n\n2.  **Identify the Initial Time (t<sub>i</sub>) and Final Time (t<sub>f</sub>):**  Make sure the units of time are consistent (e.g., seconds).  Sometimes, the initial time is assumed to be 0.\n\n3.  **Calculate the Change in Velocity (\u0394v):** Subtract the initial velocity from the final velocity.\n\n4.  **Calculate the Change in Time (\u0394t):** Subtract the initial time from the final time.\n\n5.  **Divide the Change in Velocity by the Change in Time:** This will give you the average acceleration.\n\n**Units:**\n\n*   Velocity is typically measured in meters per second (m/s) or kilometers per hour (km/h).\n*   Time is typically measured in seconds (s).\n*   Therefore, average acceleration is typically measured in meters per second squared (m/s\u00b2) or kilometers per hour per second (km/h/s).\n\n**Example:**\n\nA car accelerates from rest (0 m/s) to 25 m/s in 5 seconds.  What is the average acceleration?\n\n1.  v<sub>i</sub> = 0 m/s\n2.  v<sub>f</sub> = 25 m/s\n3.  t<sub>i</sub> = 0 s\n4.  t<sub>f</sub> = 5 s\n\na<sub>avg</sub> = (25 m/s - 0 m/s) / (5 s - 0 s) = 25 m/s / 5 s = 5 m/s\u00b2\n\nThe average acceleration of the car is 5 m/s\u00b2.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Average vs. Instantaneous Acceleration:** Average acceleration is the *overall* change in velocity over a period of time. Instantaneous acceleration is the acceleration at a specific *moment* in time. To find instantaneous acceleration, you would need calculus (the derivative of velocity with respect to time).  This explanation focuses on *average* acceleration.\n\n*   **Constant Acceleration:** If the acceleration is constant, the average acceleration will be the same as the instantaneous acceleration at any point during the time interval.\n\n*   **Deceleration:**  Deceleration is just acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity.  A negative value for acceleration indicates deceleration if the velocity is positive.  If both velocity and acceleration are negative, the object is speeding up in the negative direction.\n",
